english:
  title: A Letter Accompanying a Mongol Official
  author: Lee Gyeou-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I humbly submit this letter. On this day of the current month, our nation's envoys have arrived, and I have learned that your command has newly taken charge of the great army, unfurling the banners of authority not yet a full month past. Yet your renown already shakes the realm, and all the peoples of the lands cannot help but open their eyes and see anew. Nearly all who behold such virtue stand transformed. How much more so for our small nation? Our joy and excitement surpasses ordinary measure a thousandfold. Moreover, your gracious compassion has released all our emissaries who lingered here so long. For this kindness, our gratitude is boundless, beyond what words can express.

    Regarding the matter you mentioned of my and Minister Ch'oe's appearance before you—as stated in our previous communication to the former command—we have indeed grown fearful of the great power, having withdrawn into these mountains and seas. Thus each day our dread of approaching grows, making it difficult for us to comply. Yet our reverence remains steadfast and sincere. How could there be other considerations? I humbly beg that you understand our circumstances and grant us forbearance.

    Concerning the dispatch of Cho the cavalry commander you mentioned—he remains bedridden with illness and has not yet recovered—I cannot comply immediately. Otherwise, Suk-chang, being well-versed in travel to the great kingdom, would hardly balk at going now. As for Song Lip-chang, upon hearing the former command's orders, we promptly sent men to the exile island to apprehend him. We have waited long, but the winds and waves have been fierce, leaving us without word. Thus we have not yet sent him back, and my shame is immeasurable. The comings and goings of our nation's envoys before the Great Emperor rest wholly upon your direction. I earnestly beg that you speak well of us and convey our submission to the imperial court. This would be most auspicious.

    My anxiety is endless and I am unequal to this task. With these inadequate words, I bow twice in respectful submission.
  footnotes:
    - The 'Lotus Tent' (蓮幕) was a symbol of Mongol military command and authority.
    - This letter represents the diplomatic correspondence between the Goryeo kingdom and Mongol officials during the period of Mongol overlordship in Korea.
    - References to various officials and the mention of envoys reflect the complex tributary relationship between Goryeo and the Mongol Empire.
